on.The study concludes that provinces with large francophone populations could reduce spending on services by contracting them out and instituting a user pay system.Â© Copyright (c) Postmedia NewsÂ Â Â E-mail this ArticlePrint this ArticleShare this ArticleÂ Â Â Â Location refreshed Â Story ToolsÂ E-mail this ArticlePrint this ArticleÂ Font:*****Â Image:****Â Â Â Related Stories from Around the Web Bilingual spending costs $2.4 billion per year Â Canada.com Â Monday, January 16, 2012 Bilingualism under threat Â Full Comment Â Wednesday, October 19, 2011 Is the rest of Canada ready for Funkytown? Â Showbiz Chez Nous Â Thursday, February 03, 2011 Â Â Â The requirement for bilingualism in provincial and federal governments costs $2.4 billion per year, according to a new report from the Fraser Institute.Photograph by: Aaron Lynett, National PostÂ Â Â E-mail this GalleryPrint this GalleryShare this GalleryÂ Â Â Photo Galleries » More Photo Galleries Â Â» Photos of the daySee our editors' choices of the most eye-catching ...more Â»Â Photos: International Rythmic ...The International Rythmic Gymnastics event takes place...more Â»Â Photos: Eyes on the guys at menswear...Prada certainly knows how to steal the spotlight. ...more Â»Â More Photo Galleries » Â Â Related Topics OntarioQuebecCulture and Lifestyle Most Popular News Most Read E-mailed Commented Pop Forecast: Haywire is ready to rumble Montreal bands have big plans in 2012 Montreal surgeon pioneers revolutionary technique to repair perforated eardrums Police investigating molestation cases on STM buses Montreal Canadiens win does little to raise Cole's spirits Jean-Yves Migneault guilty in abduction, sexual assault of woman in Montreal Â more Â» RSS Tim Horton's doubles down on cup size Montreal scientists discover origins of rare neurological disease T-shirt parties are all the rage Montreal surgeon pioneers revolutionary technique to repair perforated eardrums New Cirque du Soleil show to be called Amaluna Crosby w